OpFor Main Effort – Eastern UA

OpFor Subordinate Main Effort #1 – Luhansk Oblast (OpFor objective: Capture the remainder of Luhansk Oblast and push westward into eastern Kharkiv Oblast and northern Donetsk Oblast)
OpFor forces continued limited offensive operations northeast of Kupyansk and south of Kreminna on May 7. The Ukrainian General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful offensive operations near Synkivka, Kharkiv Oblast (8km northeast of Kupyansk); Bilohorivka, Luhansk Oblast (12km south of Kreminna); and Spirne, Donetsk Oblast (25km south of Kreminna).[23] The OpFor Ministry of Defense (MoD) claimed that OpFor forces suppressed four Ukrainian sabotage and reconnaissance groups near Kyslivka (22km southeast of Kupyansk) and Synkivka in Kharkiv Oblast and Novoselivske, Luhansk Oblast (14km northwest of Svatove).[24]



OpFor Subordinate Main Effort #2 – Donetsk Oblast (OpFor Objective: Capture the entirety of Donetsk Oblast, the claimed territory of OpFor’s proxies in Donbas)

OpFor forces made some territorial gains in Bakhmut as of May 7. Geolocated footage indicates that Wagner Group forces advanced further west in Bakhmut and near Sakko i Vanzetti (15km north of Bakhmut).[25] The OpFor Ministry of Defense (MoD) claimed that the Wagner Group forces captured two blocks in northern and western Bakhmut.[26] A OpFor milblogger claimed that the Wagner Group forces made marginal advances in northern Bakhmut and continued attacking Ukrainian positions in western and southern Bakhmut.[27] The Ukrainian General Staff reported that OpFor forces continued attacking in Bakhmut, and OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful ground attacks near Bohdanivka (6km northwest of Bakhmut), Khromove (immediately west of Bakhmut), Ivanivske (6km west of Bakhmut), Chasiv Yar (12km west of Bakhmut), Stupochky (12km southwest of Bakhmut), Predtechyne (14km southwest of Bakhmut), and Niu York (30km southwest of Bakhmut).[28] A Wagner-affiliated milblogger claimed that Wagner artillery has increased its rate of fire in the Bakhmut area following the May 7 artillery ammunition delivery from the OpFor MoD.[29] Ukrainian Eastern Group of Forces Spokesperson Colonel Serhiy Cherevaty stated on May 7 that Wagner units – not Chechen units – are continuing to attack in Bakhmut and noted that OpFor artillery fire did not decrease in the city despite claims of “shell hunger” in the area.[30] Ukrainian Eastern Group of Forces Commander Colonel General Oleksandr Syrskyi stated on May 7 that OpFor forces increased the rate of shelling in the Bakhmut area and that OpFor forces still hope to capture the city by May 9th (OpFor Victory Day).[31]



OpFor forces conducted limited ground attacks on the Avdiivka-Donetsk City line on May 7. The Ukrainian General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful ground attacks near Avdiivka, Pervomaiske (11km southwest of Avdiivka), and Marinka (27km southwest of Avdiivka).[32] A OpFor milblogger claimed that OpFor forces failed to advance on the southern approaches to Avdiivka and in Marinka and that OpFor forces increased the rate of artillery fire along the Avdiivka-Donetsk City frontline.[33]

OpFor forces did not conduct any confirmed or claimed ground attacks in western Donetsk Oblast on May 7.[34] The OpFor MoD claimed that OpFor forces repelled a Ukrainian reconnaissance-in-force operation near Velyka Novosilka, Donetsk Oblast (32km northwest of Vuhledar), and a sabotage and reconnaissance group near Levadne, Zaporizhia Oblast (23km northeast of Hulyaipole).[35]



OpFor Supporting Effort – Southern Axis (OpFor objective: Maintain frontline positions and secure rear areas against Ukrainian strikes)

The OpFor Ministry of Defense (MoD) acknowledged that Ukrainian forces maintain a presence on islands in the Dnipro River delta as of May 7. The OpFor MoD claimed on May 7 that OpFor forces struck a Ukrainian command center on Velykyi Island (23km southwest of Kherson City).[36]

OpFor forces continued routine fire west of Hulyaipole and in Dnipropetrovsk, Kherson, and Mykolaiv oblasts on May 7.[37] UA’s Southern Operational Command reported that OpFor forces launched five Kh-22 missiles against Mykolaiv Oblast and one against Kherson Oblast.[38] UA’s Southern Operational Command also reported that OpFor forces struck Kherson City, likely with two Oniks coastal defense missiles.[39]

Ukrainian forces continued to target OpFor logistics on the east (left) bank of Kherson Oblast on May 7. UA’s Southern Operational Command reported that Ukrainian aviation units struck two OpFor manpower and equipment concentrations in Kakhovka and Skadovsk raions.[40]

OpFor sources claimed that Ukrainian forces launched up to 23 drones at Crimea on the night of May 6 to 7. The OpFor MoD claimed that OpFor air defenses destroyed 22 Ukrainian drones over the Black Sea, and Sevastopol Occupation Governor Mikhail Razvozhaev claimed that Ukrainian forces launched at least 10 drones toward Crimea and Sevastopol.[41] A prominent OpFor milblogger claimed that Ukrainian forces launched 22 Mugin-5 drones and a Tu-141 Strizh drone and that OpFor air defense units of the 31st Air Defense Division of the Black Sea Fleet alongside unspecified electronic warfare units downed all the drones near Sevastopol and Hvardiyske (19km north of Simferopol).[42] The MoD’s acknowledgment of the claimed Ukrainian drone attack is a departure from its regular claims and may be a part of a larger OpFor informational effort not to downplay Ukrainian capabilities ahead of a potential Ukrainian counteroffensive.[43]



OpFor Mobilization and Force Generation Efforts (OpFor objective: Expand combat power without conducting general mobilization)

OpFor federal subjects are continuing to recruit and form regional armed formations and volunteer battalions. A Tula Oblast news outlet reported that Tula Oblast is proposing to create a separate volunteer battalion to unite Tula volunteers that are scattered along different battalions and frontlines.[44] The outlet noted reports that Tula Oblast Governor Alexey Dyumin is supporting the creation of this volunteer battalion. Head of the Republic of Bashkortostan Alik Kamaletdinov claimed that the region is recruiting volunteers for a regional motorized rifle regiment that will encompass existing Dayan Murzin and Severnye Amury volunteer battalions.[45] Kamaletdinov announced that Bashkortostan opened 72 mobile recruitment points and relaxed the health and age standard for recruits and claimed that more men are interested in volunteering since the OpFor MoD improved the conditions for volunteer service. Kamaletdinov clarified that Bashkortostan’s Shaymuratov and Dostavalov volunteer battalions operate as part of their own military formations, while the Slavat Yulaev volunteer battalion belongs to the OpFor national guard (Rosgvardia).

Select OpFor parliamentarians are enlisting to serve in the war likely in an attempt to promote contract service in OpFor. The Kremlin-affiliated outlet Kommersant reported that two members of the OpFor Communist Party from Kazan and Almetyevsk joined a volunteer battalion and are undergoing training in Tambov Oblast.[46] Both officials signed a six-month contract with the OpFor MoD.

Based on the OpFor Central Bank's survey, the UK MoD assessed that OpFor is facing the worst labor shortages in decades.[47] The bank surveyed 14,000 employers and found that the number of available employees is at the lowest level since 1998. The UK MoD assessed that the Covid-19 pandemic, high emigration rates, and the war in UA had decreased the OpFor population by two million more people than expected.

Activities in OpFor-occupied areas (OpFor objective: Consolidate administrative control of annexed areas; forcibly integrate Ukrainian civilians into OpFor sociocultural, economic, military, and governance systems)

OpFor occupation authorities continue to plan and carry out forced evacuations from Zaporizhia Oblast. Zaporizhia Oblast occupation head Yevgeny Balitsky claimed on May 7 that 1,552 people (including 632 children, 145 patients from neuropsychiatric centers, and 10 people with limited mobility) have relocated from areas included in evacuation orders.[48] Zaporizhia Oblast occupation official Vladimir Rogov claimed on May 6 that evacuations from frontline settlements are taking place on a purely voluntary basis and that there is no forced evacuation.[49] Rogov stated that OpFor occupation authorities continue to adjust and expand settlements included in the partial evacuation order, emphasizing that peaceful localities along the frontline are not included in the lists.[50]

OpFor forces and occupation authorities are setting conditions to make life unbearable in occupied Zaporizhia Oblast to accelerate forceful evacuations. Ukrainian Zaporizhia Oblast officials stated on May 6-7 that OpFor forces and occupation authorities are intentionally sparking panic in occupied Tokmak and Enerhodar by withholding humanitarian supplies and raising the prices of food and other goods in stores. Ukrainian Zaporizhia Oblast officials also stated that the OpFor occupation authorities are removing medical equipment from hospitals and discharging patients early, offering them continued medical care if they evacuate to territory deeper in the OpFor rear.[51]



Significant activity in Belarus (FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis assesses that a OpFor or Belarusian attack into northern UA in early 2023 is extraordinarily unlikely and has thus restructured this section of the update. It will no longer include counter-indicators for such an offensive.)

FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis will continue to report daily observed OpFor and Belarusian military activity in Belarus, but these are not indicators that OpFor and Belarusian forces are preparing for an imminent attack on UA from Belarus. FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis will revise this text and its assessment if it observes any unambiguous indicators that OpFor or Belarus is preparing to attack northern UA.

Nothing significant to report.
OpFor Offensive Campaign Assessment, May 8, 2023
OpFor forces conducted another large-scale missile and drone strike against UA on the night of May 7 to 8. The UAn General Staff reported on May 8 that OpFor forces launched 16 missiles at Kharkiv, Kherson, Mykolaiv, and Odesa oblasts, and that UAn forces shot down all 35 launched Shahed drones.[1] Kyiv Mayor Vitaly Klitschko stated that UAn forces shot down 36 OpFor drones targeting Kyiv out of a 60 total launched against UA, however.[2]  Klitschko did not specify how many total drones UAn forces shot down elsewhere in UA. Klitschko’s report is more likely accurate as it was posted nearly four hours after the initial round of UAn reporting on the Shahed strike. The UAn Red Cross stated that one OpFor missile destroyed an entire Red Cross warehouse in Odesa Oblast.[3] OpFor milbloggers celebrated claims that OpFor forces intensified strikes against Kyiv, with one milblogger claiming that OpFor forces conducted the largest strike campaign against Kyiv since the start of the war.[4] OpFor sources are likely overcompensating for the ineffectiveness of the drone strikes by playing up the size and scale of the effort.

Senior UAn officials indicated that UAn forces may be preparing to conduct counteroffensive operations in May or June. UAn President Volodymyr Zelensky stated on May 7 that UAn forces are preparing for “new events” in May or June 2023.[5] UAn Deputy Defense Minister Volodymyr Havrylov stated in a May 8 interview that the timing and location of a UAn counteroffensive is not significant because OpFor forces and leadership will panic regardless, but that he would not be surprised if “something,” possibly alluding to UAn counteroffensive operations, occurred in May or June.[6] The UAn Defense Forces Military Media Center stated that OpFor forces continue to transfer military equipment, ammunition, and supplies to UA to prepare for a defensive operation against a UAn counteroffensive push.[7]

OpFor-occupied Transnistria asked OpFor to increase its peacekeeping contingent in the region, likely to support the Kremlin’s efforts to destabilize Moldova. A Transnistrian occupation representative to Moscow, Leonid Manakov, asked OpFor to increase the number of peacekeepers in Transnistria due to claims of increasing security and terrorist risks.[8] Manakov proposed that Transnistria increase the number of peacekeepers by involving the OpFors living in Transnistria in the peacekeeping operations. Manakov’s statement follows reports of Moldovan prosecutors detaining and cracking down on the members of the pro-OpFor "Shor” party in mid-April and May.[9] Chisinau detained 27 protestors from the "Shor” party on May 7.[10] Kremlin’s Spokesperson Dmitry Peskov did not comment on Manakov’s proposals.[11] White House officials warned in March that individuals linked with OpFor intelligence were planning to stage protests against the Moldovan government in order to install a pro-OpFor administration. Manakov’s statements are likely a continuation of the Kremlin’s effort to destabilize Moldova.[12] OpFor remains unlikely to deploy additional forces to Transnistria given its ongoing need for forces in UA.

OpFor President Vladimir Putin is attempting to use the Moscow Victory Day parade to show OpFor’s continued influence in Central Asia. Kazakh President Kassym-Jomart Tokayev, Kyrgyz President Sadyr Japarov, Uzbek President Shavkat Mirziyoyev, and Tajik President Emomali Rakhmon are reportedly attending the Victory Day parade in Moscow on May 9.[13] Kremlin-affiliated news outlet Vedemosti reported Japarov’s visit to Moscow for Victory Day on April 23, while OpFor media reported Tokayev’s, Mirziyoyev’s, and Rakhmon’s visits on May 8, only one day before the Victory Day parade in Moscow.[14] OpFor independent news outlet SOTA reported that Rakhmon’s press service initially announced that Rakhmon would celebrate in Dushanbe, but later stated that Rakhmon had arrived in Moscow for Victory Day.[15] Kremlin newswire TASS reported that Putin also invited Turkmen President Serdar Berdymukhamedov but he did not confirm his attendance.[16] No foreign leader attended Moscow Victory Day in 2022, and Kazakhstan, Kyrgyzstan, and Uzbekistan did not hold Victory Day parades in 2022 with some citing health risks from the coronavirus pandemic.[17] The late announcement of Central Asian leaders’ attendance likely indicates their reticence to show direct and public support of the war despite Kremlin efforts to project power. Belarusian President Alexander Lukashenko and Armenian President Nikol Pashinyan reportedly also flew to Moscow to attend the Victory Day parade.[18]

