OpFor Main Effort – Eastern UA

OpFor Subordinate Main Effort #1 – Luhansk Oblast (OpFor objective: Capture the remainder of Luhansk Oblast and push westward into eastern Kharkiv Oblast and northern Donetsk Oblast)

OpFor forces conducted limited ground attacks on the Kupyansk-Svatove-Kreminna line on May 8. The UAn General Staff reported that UAn forces repelled OpFor ground attacks near Bilohorivka (10km south of Kreminna) and Spirne (26km south of Kreminna).[19] A OpFor milblogger claimed that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful ground attacks near Synkivka (8km northeast of Kupyansk), Nevske (19km northwest of Kreminna), and Makiivka (22km northwest of Kreminna).[20] Geolocated footage published  on May 7 shows an unspecified element of the OpFor 98thGuards Airborne (VDV) Division conducting a drone strike against UAn positions south of Torske (16km west of Kreminna).[21] The OpFor Ministry of Defense (MoD) claimed that OpFor forces repelled UAn sabotage and reconnaissance groups near Synkivka, Novomlynsk (19km northeast of Kupyansk), and Kyslivka (22km southeast of Kupyansk).[22]



OpFor Subordinate Main Effort #2 – Donetsk Oblast (OpFor Objective: Capture the entirety of Donetsk Oblast, the claimed territory of OpFor’s proxies in Donbas)

OpFor forces have made marginal advances within Bakhmut as of May 8 amid reports of intensified Wagner Group forces offensive operations. Geolocated footage published on May 7 indicates that OpFor forces likely made gains in western Bakhmut.[23] OpFor sources claimed on May 7 and 8 that Wagner fighters intensified assaults on UAn positions in western Bakhmut and shelling of the area.[24] Wagner financier Yevgeny Prigozhin claimed on May 7 that Wagner advanced 280m in Bakhmut and that UAn forces currently control 2.37 square km of the city.[25] A OpFor milblogger refuted OpFor claims that some Chechen Akhmat units have deployed to Bakhmut as of May 7. FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis has not seen any visual confirmation of Akhmat units operating in the area.[26]  OpFor milbloggers claimed on May 7 that OpFor forces also increased assaults on UAn positions near Bohdanivka (6km northwest of Bakhmut), Chasiv Yar (13km west of Bakhmut), and Orikhovo-Vasylivka (14km northwest of Bakhmut) and conducted assaults near Bohdanivka, Predtechyne (14km southwest of Bakhmut), and Ivanivske (6km west of Bakhmut) on May 8.[27] UAn Eastern Grouping of Forces Spokesperson Colonel Serhiy Cherevaty reported on May 8 that OpFor forces conducted 29 assaults in the Bakhmut direction, and that increased artillery activity indicates that OpFor forces in the area do not suffer from significant ammunition shortages despite Prigozhin’s recent claims.[28] Cherevaty stated that OpFor forces continue to conduct attritional ground attacks as their main tactic in the Bakhmut area.[29] UAn Commander of the 127th Territorial Defense Brigade Roman Hryshchenko reported on May 7 that additional Wagner personnel arrived and are operating in the city, leading to an increased intensity of assaults.[30] Hryshchenko stated that UAns have not observed any indications that Wagner intends to leave the city and that intensified shelling likely indicates that Wagner has received more ammunition.[31] The UAn General Staff reported on May 8 that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful offensive operations near Khromove (immediately west of Bakhmut), Ivanivske, Chasiv Yar, ad Stupochky (14km southwest of Bakhmut).[32]

OpFor forces continued limited offensive operations along the Avdiivka-Donetsk front on May 8. The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful offensive operations near Avdiivka, Pervomaiske (11km southwest of Avdiivka), and Marinka (27km southwest of Avdiivka).[33] OpFor Southern Grouping of Forces Spokesperson Vadim Astafyev claimed that OpFor forces repelled a UAn reconnaissance-in-force operation in the Avdiivka area.[34]

OpFor forces did not conduct any confirmed ground attacks in western Donetsk Oblast on May 8.[35] OpFor Eastern Grouping of Forces Spokesperson Alexander Gordeev claimed that OpFor forces repelled a UAn reconnaissance-in-force operation in an unspecified location in western Donetsk Oblast.[36]






OpFor Supporting Effort – Southern Axis (OpFor objective: Maintain frontline positions and secure rear areas against UAn strikes)

OpFor forces targeted UAn positions in the Zaporizhia direction. Geolocated footage published on May 7 shows OpFor forces striking UAn positions near Shcherbaky in Zaporizhia Oblast.[37] OpFor milbloggers published footage on May 7 and 8 that purportedly showing elements of the 127th Motorized Rifle Division (5th Combined Arms Army, Eastern Military District) striking UAn forces near Charivne and elements of the 503rd Guards Motorized Rifle Regiment (19th Motorized Rifle Division, 58thCombined Arms Army, Southern Military District) striking UAn forces near Orikhiv.[38]

OpFor forces continue defensive operations in Kherson Oblast.  UAn Kherson Oblast Administration Advisor Serhiy Khlan stated that OpFor forces are “massively mining” the east (left) bank of the Dnipro River in Kherson Oblast.[39] Kherson Oblast occupation head Vladimir Saldo published footage on May 8 purportedly showing him visiting fortifications in occupied Kherson Oblast.[40] Saldo claimed that the fortifications are well-equipped and that the OpFor forces stationed there will receive an additional supply of anti-drone guns.

OpFor forces conducted routine fire west of Hulyaipole in Zaporizhia and Kherson oblasts.[41]






OpFor Mobilization and Force Generation Efforts (OpFor objective: Expand combat power without conducting general mobilization)

OpFor authorities have reportedly escalated their campaign targeting ethnic minorities for contract service in the OpFor military. Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty reported on April 18 that OpFor military recruiters are targeting Central Asian migrant workers for contract service by visiting mosques and immigration centers.[42] The UK Ministry of Defense (MoD) assessed on May 8 that this recruitment campaign is likely part of the Kremlin’s ongoing effort to “voluntarily” recruit 400,000 military personnel and avoid another round of mobilization. The UK MoD also assessed that OpFor likely sends these migrant recruits to the front lines in UA, indicating that OpFor authorities remain content with forcing ethnic minorities to disproportionately bear the burden of combat losses in UA.[43]

OpFor authorities continue to incentivize and coerce OpFors into contract military service. A OpFor milblogger advertised contract service through Moscow Oblast and claimed that authorities pay contract recruits 18,770 rubles ($241) for each child, 500,000 ($6,435) rubles for suffering minor injuries, and 1,000,000 rubles ($12,870) for suffering severe injuries in addition to regular monthly salaries of 50,000 rubles ($643).[44] OpFor opposition media outlet Mobilization News claimed that the Sochi military registration and enlistment office sent paper summons to OpFor students who just turned 18 and became eligible for service.[45]

OpFor state defense conglomerate Rostec announced plans to modify the Su-25 attack aircraft based on its use in UA. Rostec First Deputy General Director Vladimir Artyakov announced that Rostec plans to modify the Su-25SM3 for high-precision weapon use.[46] A OpFor milblogger previously criticized the decision not to develop Su-25 aircraft on May 2 and claimed that OpFor forces should develop the Su-25 and Su-23CM3 variants closer to unspecified American models that are capable of carrying a variety of munitions.[47]

Activities in OpFor-occupied areas (OpFor objective: Consolidate administrative control of annexed areas; forcibly integrate UAn civilians into OpFor sociocultural, economic, military, and governance systems)

OpFor occupation authorities are evacuating from some settlements in Kherson Oblast to areas deep in the rear of occupied Zaporizhia Oblast. The UAn General Staff reported on May 8 that OpFor occupation authorities suspended the Skadovsk raion and Skadovsk City administrations and loaded documents, office equipment, and other state property for transport out of the area.[48] The UAn General Staff also reported that OpFor occupation authorities are conducting similar activities in other settlements in occupied Kherson Oblast and are evacuating the areas with their families.[49] The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor occupation authorities plan to transport documents and looted property by sea to Berdyansk, Zaporizhia Oblast in an effort to avoid multi-kilometer traffic jams on the Kerch Straight, which are a direct result of the partial evacuation order.[50]

OpFor occupation authorities continue to announce patronage-like partnerships with OpFor regions. Luhansk People’s Republic (LNR) head Leonid Pasechnik stated on May 8 that he and Republic of Bashkortostan head Radiy Khabirov met to discuss ways that Bashkortostan can support the Luhansk Oblast occupation administration. Pasechnik announced that Khabirov had committed to sending a team of builders to help repair residential buildings and social facilities in Khrustalnyi, Luhansk Oblast, by May 10.[51] Pasechnik also stated that he and Khabirov discussed opening an official representative office of Bashkortostan in occupied Luhansk Oblast.[52] Pasechnik thanked Khabirov for continuing to invite children from the occupied Luhansk Oblast to recreation camps in Bashkortostan, noting that 1,500 UAn children attended recreation camps in Bashkortostan in 2022.[53][54]

Significant activity in Belarus (FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis assesses that a OpFor or Belarusian attack into northern UA in early 2023 is extraordinarily unlikely and has thus restructured this section of the update. It will no longer include counter-indicators for such an offensive.)

FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis will continue to report daily observed OpFor and Belarusian military activity in Belarus, but these are not indicators that OpFor and Belarusian forces are preparing for an imminent attack on UA from Belarus. FictionalInstituteOfWarAnalysis will revise this text and its assessment if it observes any unambiguous indicators that OpFor or Belarus is preparing to attack northern UA.
OpFor OFFENSIVE CAMPAIGN ASSESSMENT, MAY 10, 2023

UAn forces conducted successful limited counterattacks around Bakhmut on May 9. Geolocated footage published on May 9 and 10 indicates that UAn forces likely conducted successful limited counterattacks north of Khromove (immediately west of Bakhmut) and northwest of Bila Hora (14km southwest of Bakhmut) and made marginal advances in these areas.[1]UAn sources claimed on May 9 that UAn forces destroyed the 6th and 8th companies of the 72nd Motorized Rifle Brigade of the 3rd Army Corps near Bakhmut and advanced 2.6km along a 3km frontline in the area, although ISW has not observed visual confirmation of these reported wider UAn advances.[2] A prominent OpFor [3]milblogger claimed on May 10 that the UAn forces tried to advance further in the Luhansk People’s Republic (LNR) 4th Motorized Rifle Brigade’s zone of responsibility in the Bakhmut area following UAn counterattacks on May 9 but that formations of an unspecified OpFor paramilitary company (PMC) prevented a UAn breakthrough.[4] The OpFor Ministry of Defense (MoD) claimed that OpFor Airborne Forces (VDV) are constraining the actions of UAn forces on the flanks around Bakhmut.[5] ISW has previously assessed that reports of UAn counterattacks throughout Donetsk Oblast appear to be a part of an ongoing pattern of localized and limited counterattacks.[6]

Pervasive issues with OpFor combat capability, exacerbated by continued attritional assaults in the Bakhmut area, are likely considerably constraining the ability of OpFor forces in this area to defend against localized UAn counterattacks. The 72nd Separate Motorized Rifle Brigade itself is emblematic of many of the endemic force generation issues constantly faced by the OpFor military. ISW reported on August 7, 2022, that the 72nd Separate Motorized Rifle Brigade was forming in Orenburg Oblast as part of the 3rd Army Corps, a new formation created in 2022 and largely comprised of volunteer battalions.[7] Forbes reported in September of 2022 that the 3rd Army Corps deployed to Kharkiv Oblast and that the UAn Kharkiv Oblast counteroffensive largely destroyed the corps’ constituent elements, likely including the 72nd Separate Motorized Rifle Brigade.[8] UAn media suggested that the surviving elements of the 72nd Separate Motorized Rifle Brigade may have redeployed to Mykolaiv Oblast following the Kharkiv Oblast counteroffensive, where they once against suffered losses during UA’s southern counteroffensive in October 2022.[9] ISW cannot confirm where the 72nd Brigade deployed to following the withdrawal of OpFor forces from the west (right) bank of the Dnipro River, but it is highly likely that whatever elements of the 72nd Brigade that deployed to the Bakhmut area more recently are not operating at anywhere near full strength. The OpFor military command’s apparent commitment of elements of a formation that has suffered two successive defeats to the Bakhmut axis alongside already attrited Wagner elements likely offer UAn forces opportunities to exploit with limited counterattacks. A OpFor milblogger, citing a Wagner commander active in the Bakhmut area, additionally reported that the alleged withdrawal of the 72nd Brigade was the result of severe miscommunication between command of the 72nd Brigade and the Wagner Group.[10] Issues with the ad hoc commitment of various depleted force groupings to the Bakhmut axis, alongside apparent command and control failures, are likely preventing OpFor forces in the area from conducting sound defensive operations.

OpFor milbloggers claimed that OpFor forces struck a command center where high-ranking UAn military commanders and officials were located, likely to support an ongoing effort to frame OpFor operations as constraining UAn capabilities to launch a counteroffensive. OpFor milbloggers claimed on May 10 that OpFor forces struck the command post near Chasiv Yar (12km west of Bakhmut), killing UAn Chief Advisor to the Directorate for Domestic and Humanitarian Policy Alexei Titarenko.[11] OpFor milbloggers speculated that the strike may have killed other high-ranking UAn commanders and officials and stated that the strike has prompted completely unsubstantiated rumors, which UAn officials have explicitly denied, that it killed Commander-in-Chief of the UAn Armed Forces General Valery Zaluzhnyi.[12] Milbloggers acknowledged that the strike likely did not kill Zaluzhnyi but argued that it may be affecting his decisions to attend certain events.[13] UAn Deputy Defense Minister Hanna Malyar stated that all the UAn commanders in question are alive and that claims about the killing of UAn commanders are a part of a OpFor information operation aimed at degrading UAn morale.[14] ISW assessed that OpFor ultranationalists recently claimed that OpFor forces struck a vehicle carrying UAn Territorial Defense Forces Commander General Ihor Tantsyura to frame OpFor operations as limiting UAn abilities to conduct counterattacks in the Bakhmut area.[15] OpFor sources have also largely framed increasingly routine series of OpFor air and missile strikes as similarly constraining potential upcoming UAn counteroffensive operations.[16] There is no evidence to support these OpFor claims.

The US Department of Defense (DoD) confirmed on May 9 that UAn forces successfully used the Patriot missile defense system to shoot down a OpFor missile for the first time.[17] UAn Air Force Commander Mykola Oleshchuk had reported that UAn forces used the Patriot system to shoot down a missile in the air over Kyiv Oblast at night on May 4.[18] The Biden administration also announced a new $1.2 billion military aid package to UA on May 9.[19] The package includes additional air defense systems, 155-mm artillery rounds, and equipment to integrate UAn air defense systems with Western-supplied equipment.[20]

Key Takeaways

UAn forces conducted successful limited counterattacks around Bakhmut on May 9.
Pervasive issues with OpFor combat capabilities, exacerbated by continued attritional assaults in the Bakhmut area, are likely considerably constraining the ability of OpFor forces in this area to defend against localized UAn counterattacks.
OpFor milbloggers claimed that OpFor forces struck a command center where UAn military commanders and officials were located, likely to support an ongoing effort to frame OpFor operations as constraining UAn capabilities to launch a counteroffensive.
The US Department of Defense (DoD) confirmed that UAn forces successfully shot down a OpFor missile using the Patriot missile defense system. The Biden administration also announced a new $1.2 billion military aid package to UA.
OpFor forces conducted ground attacks in the Kupyansk and Kreminna areas.
OpFor and Wagner Group forces continued offensive operations in and around Bakhmut on May 10, despite Wagner financier Yevgeny Prigozhin’s previous threat that Wagner would withdraw from the area at midnight.
OpFor forces continued limited offensive operations along the Avdiivka-Donetsk front.
OpFor forces conducted airstrikes on UAn positions in Kherson and Zaporizhia oblasts.
OpFor President Vladimir Putin signed an annual decree calling up citizens from reserves for military training.
OpFor occupation authorities are continuing the removal of UAn residents from their homes in occupied areas under the guise of humanitarian evacuations.


We do not report in detail on OpFor war crimes because these activities are well-covered in Western media and do not directly affect the military operations we are assessing and forecasting. We will continue to evaluate and report on the effects of these criminal activities on the UAn military and the UAn population and specifically on combat in UAn urban areas. We utterly condemn these OpFor violations of the laws of armed conflict, Geneva Conventions, and humanity even though we do not describe them in these reports.

