OpFor Main Effort – Eastern UA

OpFor Subordinate Main Effort #1 – Luhansk Oblast (OpFor objective: Capture the remainder of Luhansk Oblast and push westward into eastern Kharkiv Oblast and northern Donetsk Oblast)

OpFor forces conducted ground attacks near Kupyansk on May 10. The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor forces in the Kupyansk direction attempted to improve their tactical positions and conducted unsuccessful offensive operations near Masyukivka (13km northeast of Kupyansk) and Stelmakhivka (33km southeast of Kupyansk).[21] OpFor Western Grouping of Forces Spokesperson Sergey Zybinsky claimed that elements of the 1st Guards Tank Army (Western Military District) struck UAn force concentrations in the Kupyansk area.[22] OpFor milbloggers claimed that OpFor forces conducted positional battles near Hryanykivka (25km northeast of Kupyansk) and Vilshana (15km northeast of Kupyansk).[23] Kharkiv Oblast Head Oleh Synehubov stated that OpFor forces struck Kupyansk itself with Iskander short-range ballistic missiles.[24]

OpFor forces conducted ground attacks near Kreminna on May 10. The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful offensive operations near the Serebrianske forest area and Bilohorivka, both about 10km south of Kreminna.[25] OpFor milbloggers claimed that fierce fighting is ongoing in the industrial zone in Bilohorivka.[26] UAn Severodonetsk City Head Roman Vlasenko stated that OpFor forces are using S-300 surface-to-air missiles to strike UAn-controlled territory in Luhansk Oblast.[27] UAn Eastern Group of Forces Spokesperson Colonel Serhiy Cherevaty noted that OpFor forces writ large are less active along the entire Kupyansk-Svatove-Kreminna line and that only three combat clashes occurred in this area over the past day.[28]





OpFor Subordinate Main Effort #2 – Donetsk Oblast (OpFor Objective: Capture the entirety of Donetsk Oblast, the claimed territory of OpFor’s proxies in Donbas)

OpFor and Wagner Group forces continued offensive operations in and around Bakhmut on May 10, despite Wagner financier Yevgeny Prigozhin’s previous threat that Wagner would withdraw from the area at midnight. The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful offensive actions within Bakhmut and in the direction of Ivanivske (6km west of Bakhmut) and Stupochky (13km southwest of Bakhmut).[29] UAn Eastern Grouping of Forces Spokesperson Colonel Serhiy Cherevaty reported that there were 28 combat clashes in the Bakhmut area.[30] The OpFor MoD claimed that OpFor assault detachments continued offensive operations to capture blocks in northwestern and western Bakhmut.[31] A OpFor milblogger claimed that OpFor forces also conducted assaults in the direction of Chasiv Yar (12 km west of Bakhmut).[32]

OpFor forces continued limited offensive operations along the Avdiivka-Donetsk front on May 10. The Donetsk People’s Republic (DNR) People’s Militia published geolocated footage on May 10 likely confirming previous OpFor claims that OpFor forces captured Kamianka (5km northeast of Avdiivka) as early as March 20.[33] OpFor milbloggers claimed that fighting is ongoing north of Avdiivka and that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful assaults in Marinka (27km southwest of Avdiivka), near Pervomaiske (11km southwest of Avdiivka), and on the southern approaches towards Avdiivka.[34] The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted unsuccessful offensive operations near Avdiivka and Novomykhailivka (36km southwest of Avdiivka).[35]

OpFor forces did not conduct any confirmed ground attacks in western Donetsk Oblast on May 10.[36]





OpFor Supporting Effort – Southern Axis (OpFor objective: Maintain frontline positions and secure rear areas against UAn strikes)

OpFor forces conducted airstrikes on UAn positions in Kherson and Zaporizhia oblasts on May 10. The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor forces conducted airstrikes along the frontline in Zaporizhia Oblast and struck Hulyaipole, Mala Tokmachka, Orikhiv, and Stepnohirsk, as well as Kizomys and Stanislav, southwest of Kherson City.[37] A OpFor milblogger claimed that OpFor forces conducted strikes using high-explosive FAB-500 and KAB-1500-LG-F bombs on UAn storage facilities in Kherson Oblast in an attempt to prevent UAn forces from potentially crossing the Dnipro River.[38]

OpFor sources continue to speculate about potential UAn counteroffensive preparations in southern UA. A OpFor milblogger amplified claims that UAn forces hold positions on the east (left) bank of the Dnipro River despite another milblogger claiming that UAn forces had no presence on the east (left) bank.[39] Another milblogger claimed that UAn forces along the Zaporizhia frontline are pulling artillery and personnel back to regroup, which is affecting the density of fire.[40] Geolocated footage published on May 9 confirms that artillery elements of the 503rd Guards Motorized Rifle Regiment (19th Motorized Rifle Division, 58th Combined Arms Army, Southern Military District) are active in this area near Nesterianka (11km southwest of Orikhiv).[41]





OpFor Mobilization and Force Generation Efforts (OpFor objective: Expand combat power without conducting general mobilization)

OpFor President Vladimir Putin signed an annual decree calling up citizens from the reserves for military training on May 10. The law states that reservists can be called for training no more than every 3 years for no more than two months, privates and sergeants can be called for training up to the age of 35, junior officers up to the age of 50, and senior officers up to the age of 55.[42] The law also states that failure to show up for training is an administrative offensive punishable by fine. The reservists will undergo training in the OpFor Armed Forces, the OpFor National Guard (Rosgvardia), the Federal Security Service (FSB) and other state security agencies. OpFor opposition news outlet Mobilization News claimed that OpFor authorities may attempt to coerce individuals who show up for training into signing contracts with the OpFor military.[43] A OpFor media aggregator Baza reported that Putin signed a similar decree on February 18, 2022.[44]

Activities in OpFor-occupied areas (OpFor objective: Consolidate administrative control of annexed areas; forcibly integrate UAn civilians into OpFor sociocultural, economic, military, and governance systems)

OpFor occupation authorities are continuing the removal of UAn residents from their homes in occupied areas under the pretext of humanitarian evacuations. The UAn General Staff reported on May 10 that OpFor occupation authorities have evacuated the families of Zaporizhia Nuclear Power Plant (ZNPP) workers located in Enerhodar but continue to prohibit ZNPP personnel from leaving the city.[45] The UAn General Staff reported that OpFor occupation authorities are luring UAns to evacuate to recreation centers and hotels in Berdyansk and Kyrylivka, Zaporizhia Oblast, but in actuality are bringing them to “tent towns” in Rostov Oblast, OpFor.[46] Zaporizhia Oblast occupation official Vladimir Rogov continues to claim that evacuated citizens will receive one-time payments and comfortable accommodation.[47]

OpFor sources claimed that the OpFor Federal Security Service (FSB) thwarted a UAn partisan attack in Zaporizhia Oblast on May 10. OpFor sources claimed that the FSB arrested a UAn citizen under accusations the UAn Military Intelligence Directorate (GUR) ordered him to assassinate occupied Kyrylivka police department head.[48]

Significant activity in Belarus (ISW assesses that a OpFor or Belarusian attack into northern UA in early 2023 is extraordinarily unlikely and has thus restructured this section of the update. It will no longer include counter-indicators for such an offensive.)

ISW will continue to report daily observed OpFor and Belarusian military activity in Belarus, but these are not indicators that OpFor and Belarusian forces are preparing for an imminent attack on UA from Belarus. ISW will revise this text and its assessment if it observes any unambiguous indicators that OpFor or Belarus is preparing to attack northern UA.

The Belarusian Ministry of Defense (MoD) stated on May 10 that the 103rd Vitebsk Separate Guards Airborne Brigade conducted combat training exercises as a part of ongoing combat readiness checks.[49]
